    response: "🧠 **Understanding Sexual Dysfunction** 🧠\n\nStruggling with sexual function is incredibly common and usually highly treatable. It can stem from physical issues, anxiety, trauma, or stress.\n\n1. **Vaginismus (For people with vaginas):**\n   - **What it is**: Involuntary tightening or spasms of the pelvic floor muscles, making penetration (tampons, fingers, penises, medical exams) painful or impossible.\n   - **Treatment**: Pelvic floor physical therapy, dilator therapy, and psychological counseling. It is highly curable!\n\n2. **Anorgasmia (Difficulty reaching orgasm):**\n   - Many people, especially women, do not orgasm from penetration alone. Clitoral stimulation is necessary for most. Stress, antidepressants, or lack of knowledge about one's body can also play a huge role.\n\n3. **Erectile Dysfunction (ED):**\n   - Difficulty getting or keeping an erection. In youth, this is almost always caused by **performance anxiety**, stress, or overconsumption of porn (porn-induced ED), rather than physical disease.\n\n4. **Premature Ejaculation (PE):**\n   - Ejaculating sooner than desired. Very common in young men due to excitement and anxiety. Can be managed with techniques like the \"stop-start\" method, desensitizing condoms, or counseling.\n\nNever feel ashamed—sex therapists and doctors handle these issues every single day."
