    response: "🌺 **Detailed Female Reproductive Anatomy** 🌺\n\nKnowing the correct terms empowers you to understand your body and speak to doctors accurately:\n\n- **Vulva**: The external genitalia. Includes the mons pubis, labia majora (outer lips), labia minora (inner lips), clitoris, and the openings to the urethra and vagina.\n- **Clitoris**: A highly sensitive organ located at the top of the vulva, solely dedicated to sexual pleasure. What you see is just the tip (glans); the rest of it extends deep inside the body like a wishbone!\n- **Vagina**: The internal, muscular canal that connects the vulva to the cervix. It is where menstrual blood leaves the body and where penetration occurs.\n- **Cervix**: The lower, narrow part of the uterus that opens into the vagina. It produces mucus and dilates (opens) during childbirth.\n- **Uterus (Womb)**: A pear-shaped, muscular organ where a fetus grows. Its lining (endometrium) thickens and sheds each month (your period).\n- **Ovaries**: Two small glands that store and release eggs (ovulation) and produce estrogen and progesterone.\n- **Fallopian Tubes**: Tubes connecting the ovaries to the uterus. Fertilization of an egg by a sperm usually happens here.\n- **The Hymen Myth**: The hymen is a thin, stretchy fringe of tissue at the vaginal opening. It naturally wears away from physical activity, tampons, or sex. **It does not \"break\" or pop, and an intact hymen is not a reliable indicator of virginity.**"
